{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load the four CSV files metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, compute and return a compact summary containing: 1) total row count; 2) minimum timestamp and maximum timestamp; 3) a sorted list of unique cmdb_id values (limit to first 50 if more); 4) a sorted list of unique KPI/feature names (for metric use kpi_name, for trace use trace_name, for log use log_name) limited to first 50; 5) up to the first 20 rows as a sample (include all columns). Return results as a dictionary keyed by filename. Do not plot or save files." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Loaded and summarized the four telemetry files. metric.csv has 149,772 rows spanning 2022-03-21 14:30:00 to 14:59:00 (UTC+8) with many services/pods and extensive KPI names. trace.csv and log.csv cover the same 14:30–14:59 window. error_logs.csv contains 1,540 rows (some per-second entries) with many warning messages from frontend pods. Next we should narrow candidate faulty component-KPIs via metric anomaly detection (global thresholding) before using traces and logs to localize root causes. No anomaly detection has been run yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, perform these steps and return a compact top-20 result: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in the full metric.csv (use all rows), compute the global P95 value (95th percentile) and store it. 2) Filter metric.csv rows to the target incident window: 2022-03-21 14:30:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 15:00:00+08:00 inclusive. 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name), count how many rows in the filtered window have value strictly greater than the computed global P95. Also compute for that window: the earliest timestamp when value > P95 (if any), and the maximum value observed in the window. 4) Return a table of up to top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) ranked by anomaly count (descending) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. If anomaly_count is zero for all, return top 20 by max_value_in_window descending instead. Keep output compact; do not print full time series. Store intermediate tables in kernel variables for follow-ups."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the full metric series and counted how many points in the incident window exceeded each global P95. The result table (df_stats) contains ~5002 groups; many groups show small anomaly counts (mostly 2). From the sample rows, anomalies appear at two distinct sub-windows: around the start of the window (2022-03-21T14:30:00+08:00) and later near 2022-03-21T14:57–14:58+08:00. Node-level KPIs (disk.used, fs.inodes.free/total) for node-1/2/3/4 show anomalies at 14:30, while some adservice and adservice2 JVM/thread/process CPU-related KPIs show anomalies near 14:57–14:58. error_logs.csv contains many warning messages from frontend pods starting at the beginning of the window (timestamps around 1647844200 / 2022-03-21 14:30:00+08:00), suggesting an incident at ~14:30 affecting frontend. We still need to (1) identify which components have the largest concentration of metric anomalies (to prioritize root-cause candidates), and (2) correlate those with trace and log evidence to localize each of the two failures. Next, we should aggregate anomaly counts per component to get the top candidate components and inspect their top anomalous KPIs and earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the df_stats table produced earlier (the per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) stats that include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window), aggregate to component-level and return a compact top-20 table: For each cmdb_id compute: 1) num_kpis_with_anom = count of kpi_name where anomaly_count>0; 2) total_anomaly_points = sum of anomaly_count across its kpis; 3) earliest_anomaly_timestamp across its kpis (ignore missing); 4) top_kpis = a list of up to 5 kpi_name:anomaly_count pairs with highest anomaly_count for that component (ordered). Sort results by total_anomaly_points descending and return the top 20 rows with columns [cmdb_id, num_kpis_with_anom, total_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, top_kpis]. Keep output compact (max 20 rows). Store the aggregated result in a kernel variable for follow-ups."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have computed per-(cmdb_id,kpi) global P95 thresholds and found two temporal anomaly clusters in the incident window: one cluster at the start of the window (~2022-03-21T14:30+08) with many frontend pod anomalies and node filesystem/disk KPIs, and a later cluster near 2022-03-21T14:57–14:58+08 with JVM/thread/process CPU-related anomalies concentrated on adservice/adservice2. error_logs.csv already shows many warning messages from frontend pods beginning at the start of the window, which suggests a failure around 14:30 involving frontend pods. To confirm root cause for the early failure we need log message details and trace-level error/traffic signals around 14:30 to decide whether the problem is a frontend pod-level issue or a node-level filesystem/disk issue that impacted many pods. For the later cluster (14:57–14:58), we should verify whether traces or logs show latency/error increases or GC/CPU issues in adservice to confirm root cause reason. Next step: inspect error_logs and traces around the 14:30 cluster to gather concrete evidence (message texts, counts, and trace error/row_count signals) before moving to the 14:57 cluster.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze error_logs.csv and trace.csv for the early incident (around 14:30). Perform the following and return compact, bounded outputs (store full tables in kernel variables for follow-ups):\n1) From error_logs.csv, filter rows with timestamps between 2022-03-21 14:30:00+08 and 2022-03-21 14:35:00+08 inclusive. Return: a) top 20 cmdb_id by count of messages (columns: cmdb_id, message_count); b) top 10 most frequent message texts (or their first 200 characters) with counts; c) up to 20 sample rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message). \n2) From trace.csv, filter rows with timestamps in the same 14:30–14:35 window and where trace_name contains either 'from_frontend' or 'from_root' AND where trace_name contains one of ('error_rate','row_count','duration_p95','duration_mean'). Group by (cmdb_id, trace_name) and compute: average value, maximum value, and earliest timestamp where value>0 (if any). Return the top 20 groups sorted by max value desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, avg_value, max_value, earliest_nonzero_timestamp. \nLimit all returned rows to at most 20. Keep outputs compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have two temporal anomaly clusters in the 14:30–15:00 window: an early cluster around 2022-03-21T14:30:00+08:00 with many error log warnings from frontend pods and numerous frontend-related KPI anomalies (component-level aggregation shows frontend-0/1/2/frontend2-0 as top components by anomaly points and earliest anomaly timestamps at ~14:30). There are also node-level filesystem/disk/inode KPIs anomalous at ~14:30 which may indicate node-level issues or correlated effects. A later cluster appears around 2022-03-21T14:57–14:58+08:00, where many JVM/process/thread CPU KPIs for adservice/adservice2 exceed their global P95 (earliest anomaly timestamps ~14:57–14:58) suggesting an adservice CPU/Garbage-Collection or process-CPU spike event. From logs and traces we already have strong evidence for the early failure originating at frontend pods (lots of repeated \"failed to retrieve...\" warnings beginning at 14:30 and high row_count traffic from frontend to backend at 14:30). However, to confidently choose the precise root cause reason for the early incident (frontend container heartbeat / container_last_seen vs node disk/inode exhaustion vs network packet loss) we need the specific anomalous KPI names and values for the frontends and the implicated nodes. Likewise, for the later incident we need focused inspection of adservice/adservice2 anomalous KPIs (CPU/GC) and matching traces/logs to confirm whether CPU saturation or GC activity triggered the failure. Current work narrowed candidates but the root-cause components/times/reasons are not yet finalized.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) stats table (df_stats) return a compact table filtered to these cmdb_ids: frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0, node-1, node-2, node-3, node-4, node-5, node-6, adservice, adservice2. For each matching row return columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window. Sort rows by cmdb_id ascending then anomaly_count descending then max_value_in_window descending. Limit to top 40 rows. Store result in kernel variable df_candidate_details and return only that compact table."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have narrowed candidates into two temporal clusters inside the 2022-03-21 14:30–15:00 (UTC+8) window: (A) an early failure starting ~14:30 with heavy error log activity on frontend pods (frontend-0/1/2/frontend2-0) and many frontend-related metric anomalies and node FS/disk/inode anomalies at ~14:30; and (B) a later failure around ~14:57–14:58 with JVM/process/thread CPU and related metrics anomalous on adservice/adservice2. We have per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) global P95 thresholds and anomaly counts for the window. To decide the root-cause component and reason for each failure we must (1) decide which level (pod/container vs node) shows the most significant deviation for the early cluster and (2) confirm whether adservice CPU/GC metrics represent a real fault (significant deviation and a consecutive fault period) for the late cluster. Current data shows many anomalies but mostly small counts (e.g., anomaly_count=2) — we need to quantify the anomaly severity (how far max_value_in_window exceeds global_p95) to pick the most significant fault candidates. This will help determine the root-cause level (node vs container) and identify the exact first anomalous timestamp per candidate KPI.\n\nWhat remains: compute a severity score for candidate KPI faults (relative breach over global P95) for the shortlisted components (frontend pods, nodes 1–6, adservice, adservice2) and list the top KPI faults by severity so we can pick the root cause per incident and extract the first occurrence time for the decisive fault.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) stats table (df_stats or df_candidate_details stored in kernel), compute a severity score for each row: if global_p95 != 0 then severity = (max_value_in_window - global_p95) / abs(global_p95) else severity = max_value_in_window - global_p95. Filter to cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0, node-1, node-2, node-3, node-4, node-5, node-6, adservice, adservice2]. Return a compact table (max 20 rows) of columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, max_value_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, severity. Sort by severity descending and limit to top 20. Store result in kernel variable df_severity_top20 and return only that table."
}

{
    "analysis": "We focused on the early incident (14:30–14:33). Aggregation and severity scoring show two competing candidates: frontend-1 (component-level max_severity ~13.86, earliest anomaly ~14:31–14:32) and node-2 (max_severity ~9.99, earliest anomaly 14:30:00). Error logs show heavy warning messages from frontend pods starting at ~14:30, and traces show large frontend-originated row_count at 14:30. According to the diagnosis rules, when faulty components appear at different levels and we expect a single failure, the root-cause level should be the fault with the most significant deviation from threshold. Here frontend-1 has the larger severity score than node-2, so the early failure likely originates at a frontend container (frontend-1), with the decisive KPI being large container memory-failure spikes (container_memory_failures.*) observed around 14:32. However, logs show warnings for frontend pods already at ~14:30, so we must confirm the exact first anomalous KPI data point (the first metric datapoint that breaches its global P95) for frontend-1 and inspect sample metric rows to ensure the fault is not a transient spike but a consecutive fault. We have not yet finalized the later (~14:57) failure: adservice/adservice2 CPU/thread/process metrics show anomalies near 14:57–14:58 and likely indicate a CPU/GC-related fault, but we need to confirm consecutive anomaly duration and the exact first breach timestamp.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For frontend-1: 1) From the KPI-level early-incident table already in kernel (df_early_severity), select all kpi_name rows for cmdb_id == 'frontend-1' (keep up to 10 KPIs). 2) For each selected KPI, compute and return: kpi_name, global_p95, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window; and also provide up to the first 20 metric.csv rows within the window 2022-03-21 14:30:00+08 through 2022-03-21 14:35:00+08 where cmdb_id=='frontend-1' AND kpi_name==that KPI AND value > global_p95 (include columns timestamp and value). 3) Return a compact structured result: a table of KPI-level stats (one row per KPI) and for each KPI a small sample list of anomaly rows. Limit overall output to at most 10 KPIs and 20 sample rows per KPI. Store the full returned structures in kernel variables df_frontend1_kpi_stats and dict frontend1_kpi_samples for follow-ups." 
}

